Midgaard's registry framework does not maintain a specific Brawler classification — practitioners who fight unarmed and without formal institutional affiliation fall under a general "unlicensed physical practice" category that the Civic Guard applies inconsistently. Brawlers who operate as caravan escort or guard auxiliaries file under the same labor contractor registry as armed escorts. Brawlers who operate as fighting pit participants in Midgaard's smaller entertainment venues technically require a performance license, which is issued by a different registry office than the one that would classify their activity as physical practice. This jurisdictional ambiguity has never been resolved because neither office wants primary administrative responsibility for the fighting pit economy. The Ash-and-Iron Decades militarization found Brawlers to be efficient additions to reserve depot forces — equipment-independent, functionally deployable immediately, and providing close-quarters capability that armed units lacked in specific tactical situations. Guard Command veterans with Brawler training exist in the city's current guard corps but are not tracked as a separate category.

