Kowloon's Harbor Syndic maintains a nominal licensing framework for fighting pit operators under entertainment venue provisions, which in practice functions as a monitoring mechanism rather than a control mechanism. The licensed pit circuit coexists with an unlicensed circuit that operates in warehouse districts and harbor maintenance facilities outside formal licensing coverage. Harbor Syndic enforcement corps employ Brawler-tradition practitioners in their ranks — the techniques are well-suited to harbor district enforcement work, which requires close-quarters control in cramped and cluttered spaces. The enforcement corps maintains adversarial working knowledge of active pit circuits because fighters from licensed and unlicensed pits, enforcement corps members, and informal debt enforcement workers often come from the same training lineages and maintain social relationships that cross formal institutional boundaries. The Brawler tradition is most deeply institutionally embedded in Kowloon of all five cities, both through the fighting pit economy and through the enforcement functions that depend on the same skill base.

