Rakuen's Ember Warden doctrine explicitly values Brawler capability for communal defense roles. The city's resource constraints mean that weapon-dependent fighters are more expensive to field than equipment-independent ones, and Brawler practitioners who can serve defensive roles without consuming weapon maintenance resources are valued accordingly. The Canopy Compact's collective accountability model fits reasonably well with the Brawler tradition's practical orientation — demonstration-based instruction works within community training frameworks, and the tradition's lack of institutional claims means Brawler practitioners don't create the jurisdictional tensions that more formally organized traditions sometimes produce. Rakuen also maintains informal fighting pit equivalents — practice grounds where Brawler skill is tested against resistance — as part of its training infrastructure, which keeps the tradition's quality-verification mechanism functional without the harbor district institutional context that produced the pit circuit elsewhere.

