Mafdet's harbor district has its own pit fighting circuit that predates the Kowloon circuit and operates under Maritime Law provisions that give pit operators different regulatory status than their Kowloon equivalents. The Strandline Compact's trade network creates sustained demand for physical security services, and Brawler practitioners who can provide close-quarters cargo security and dispute resolution functions find consistent employment in Mafdet's maritime economy. Harbor Wardens' Ledger Houses classify Brawler practitioners who work in security functions under labor contract registry provisions. The swift-court's jurisdiction over oath-breaking extends to fighting pit agreements — a fighter who agrees to specific match terms and violates them is subject to swift-court proceedings, which Mafdet's pit operators treat as a quality assurance mechanism that the Kowloon circuit lacks.

